From Ken Mitchum Subject Re How about a crash program in basic immunological research In article WUVMD Gary Kronk writes I have been contemplating this idea for some time as I am not a doctor but my wife is a nurse and I know a lot of doctors and The point here being that doctors and nurses do not seem to get sick nearly as much as people outside the medical This is a lovely area for anecdotes but I am sure you are on to As a physician I almost never get sick usually when something horrendous is going around I either don't get it at all or get a very mild When I do get really sick it is always something This was not the situation when I was in medical school particularly on I never had younger siblings myself and when I went on the pediatric wards I suddenly found myself confronting all sorts of infectious challenges that my body was not ready Pediatrics for me was three solid months of illness and I had a temp of when I took the final exam I think what happens is that during training and beyond we are constantly exposed to new things and we have the usual reactions to them so that later on when challenged with something it is more likely a re exposure for us so we deal with it well and get a mild I don't think it is that the immune system is hyped up in any Also don't forget that the hospital flora is very different from the home and we carry a lot of that km